05798nam a22006975i 9780822381150DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20022001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223811507 a10.1515/97808223811502doi  a(DE-B1597)553187  a(OCoLC)1058433986  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS779.26 -- I56 2001 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a320.95400aWhither China? :bIntellectual Politics in Contemporary China /cXudong Zhang. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (402 p.) :b12 b&w photos, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The Making of the Post-Tiananmen Intellectual Field: A Critical Overview -- tPart I Against the Neoliberal Dogma: Four Arguments from China -- t2. Debating Liberalism and Democracy in China in the 1990s -- t3.Whither China? The Discourse on Property Rights Reform in China -- t4. The Changing Role of Government in China -- t5. Contemporary Chinese Thought and the Question of Modernity -- tPost-Tiananmen Art -- tPart II In the Global Context -- t6. King Kong in Hong Kong: Watching the ''Handover'' from the U.S.A. -- t7. The Burdens of History: Lin Zexu (1959) and The Opium War (1997) -- t8. Mao to the Market -- t9. Chinese Consumerism and the Politics of Envy: Cargo in the 1990s? -- t10. Nationalism, Mass Culture, and Intellectual Strategies in Post-Tiananmen China -- t11. Street Scenes of Subalternity: China, Globalization, and Rights -- tAppendix In the Tiger's Lair: Socialist Everydayness Enters the Market Economy in Post-Mao China -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhither China? presents an in-depth and wide-angled picture of Chinese intellectual life during the last decade of the millennium, as China struggled to move beyond the shadow of the Tiananmen tragedy. Because many cultural and intellectual paradigms of the previous decade were left in ruins by that event, Chinese intellectuals were forced in the early 1990s to search for new analytical and critical frameworks. Soon, however, they found themselves engulfed by tidal waves of globalization, surrounded by a new social landscape marked by unabashed commodification, and stunned by a drastically reconfigured socialist state infrastructure.The contributors to Whither China? describe how, instead of spearheading the popular-mandated and state-sanctioned project of modernization, intellectuals now find themselves caught amid rapidly changing structures of economic, social, political, and cultural relations that are both global in nature and local in an irreducibly political sense. Individual essays interrogate the space of Chinese intellectual production today, lay out the issues at stake, and cover major debates and discursive interventions from the 1990s. Those who write within the Chinese context are joined by Western observers of contemporary Chinese cultural and intellectual life. Together, these two groups undertake a truly international intellectual struggle not only to interpret but to change the world.Contributors. Rey Chow, Zhiyuan Cui, Michael Dutton, Gan Yang, Harry Harootunian, Peter Hitchcock, Rebecca Karl, Louisa Schein, Wang Hui, Wang Shaoguang, Xudong Zhang  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aCui, Zhiyuan1 aYang, Gan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarootunian, Harry D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHui, Wang1 aSchein, Louisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDutton, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHitchcock, Peter